: Convolution theorem.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
By the convolution definition we can see that: 
\begin_inset Formula $\stackrel[-\infty]{\infty}{\int}f\left(t\right)g\left(-t\right)dt=h\left(0\right),$
\end_inset

and therefore:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\stackrel[-\infty]{\infty}{\int}f\left(t\right)g\left(-t\right)dt=h\left(0\right)=\mathcal{F}^{-1}\left(\mathcal{F}\left(h\left(0\right)\right)\right)=\mathcal{F}^{-1}\left(H\left(u\right)\right)\left(0\right)=\mathcal{F}^{-1}\left(F\left(u\right)G\left(u\right)\right)\left(0\right)
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
=_{\left(1\right)}\stackrel[-\infty]{\infty}{\int}F\left(u\right)G\left(u\right)e^{2\pi i0u}du=_{\left(2\right)}\stackrel[-\infty]{\infty}{\int}F\left(u\right)G\left(u\right)du
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Explanations:
\end_layout

